{"Q0":"It was tough to judge where attention was directed in videos were the attention jumped to various elements of the black background seemingly at random. When there was a more fluid motion evident in the attention patterns, it was easier to deduce using my own assumptions about how humans process/read/seek information which image sequence matched a real human. I majorly relied on the following patterns to figure out if a human's attention was shown through the sequences: centrality of the attention at the beginning of the sequence, elements of the image that seemed to draw more attention in a row of the sequence, tracking through the image from left to right or from up to down. "}

{"Q0":"When the attention began in the center of the image and then moved out further towards the bounds of the image, I believed this to be more consistent with human behavior as they study the foreground of an image before the background, even if I could not see the image myself. I looked for that centrality first, exploration second pattern to judge if a sequence was human or not most frequently. I also looked for any lags in attention in certain areas of an image, where there seemed like there must have been something of interest in that spot that drew the human's attention. I would then guess that this happened earlier in the sequence rather than later and judged the agent sequences in that way. I would also look at the direction of the attention, guessing that a human (assuming that they use an alphabet similar to English and thus read from left to right) would look through an image from left to right as they scanned through. Similarly, I guessed that a human would track an element of an image downward rather than upward, so I would judge an agent's attention sequence as more human if it seemed to travel from the top of the image (or area of the image) downward. "}
